## Methodology

### Scoring Formula
```
Inherent Risk Score = Likelihood (1–5) × Impact (1–5)
Residual Risk Score = Re-scored after controls are applied
```

### Likelihood Scale
| Score | Definition |
|---|---|
| 1 | Very Unlikely — once every 5+ years |
| 2 | Unlikely — once every 2–5 years |
| 3 | Possible — once per year |
| 4 | Likely — multiple times per year |
| 5 | Very Likely — near-certain / ongoing threat |

### Impact Scale
| Score | Definition |
|---|---|
| 1 | Negligible — no material impact |
| 2 | Minor — limited operational disruption |
| 3 | Moderate — measurable financial or reputational impact |
| 4 | Significant — major data breach or regulatory event |
| 5 | Catastrophic — business-ending or severe regulatory penalty |

### Risk Treatment Options
| Treatment | When Used |
|---|---|
| **Mitigate** | Implement controls to reduce likelihood or impact |
| **Accept** | Risk level is within tolerance; cost of control exceeds benefit |
| **Transfer** | Shift financial risk via insurance or contractual terms |
| **Avoid** | Eliminate the activity that creates the risk |

### Control Types
| Type | Definition |
|---|---|
| **Preventive** | Stops the risk event from occurring (e.g., MFA, access controls) |
| **Detective** | Identifies when risk event has occurred (e.g., logging, SIEM alerts) |
| **Corrective** | Reduces impact after a risk event (e.g., backup restoration, IR plan) |

